<h1>LG Dryer Not Heating — Causes and How We Fix It</h1>

<p>This is the most common call we get on LG dryers: the machine runs a full cycle, drum spins, blower sounds normal, timer counts down — and clothes come out completely cold and wet. We've diagnosed enough of these across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County to know that "not heating" almost always comes down to one of four components. The good news is that all four are fixable same day, and none of them require a new dryer.</p>

<h2>The Four Most Likely Causes</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    1. Thermal Fuse Blown
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Zero heat</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Dryer runs normally otherwise</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Usually caused by clogged vent</div>
  </div>
  <p>The thermal fuse is a one-shot safety device on the blower housing. When the dryer overheats — almost always because the exhaust vent is clogged — the fuse blows permanently and cuts power to the heating circuit. The dryer keeps running but produces no heat at all. It's the first thing we test on every no-heat call because it's the cheapest part and the most common cause. About 60% of our no-heat calls end here. Important: replacing the fuse without clearing the vent means the new fuse blows within weeks. We always clear and test vent airflow as part of the job. See our full <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">thermal fuse replacement</a> page.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    2. Heating Element Failed (Electric Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Electric dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Zero or weak heat</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">May trip circuit breaker</div>
  </div>
  <p>On electric LG dryers, the heating element is the coiled resistance wire that generates heat. When it fails completely, you get zero heat. When it fails partially — a break in one section of the coil — you get weak heat or intermittent heating: the dryer heats for 10–15 minutes then cuts out, or takes two or three cycles to dry a normal load. On some older homes in Beverly Hills and Santa Monica, a failed element also trips the circuit breaker. We test the element with a multimeter — a functioning LG element reads 8–12 ohms. Cost: $300–380. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    3. Gas Valve Solenoid Coils Failed (Gas Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common on gas</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Gas dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Igniter glows but burner won't light</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Brief gas smell at startup possible</div>
  </div>
  <p>On gas LG dryers, the gas valve solenoid coils control gas flow to the burner. When they fail, the igniter glows normally but the gas valve doesn't open — no gas, no flame, no heat. You might notice a brief gas odor at startup that disappears — that's the valve trying to open but failing. Symptom is identical to igniter failure which is why we test both. We've had jobs in Beverly Hills and Santa Monica where the igniter was glowing perfectly and the coils were the actual problem. Cost: coils $280–340, full valve $380–450. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-gas-valve-replacement/">gas valve replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    4. Igniter Failed (Gas Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Less common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Gas dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">No glow or dim orange glow at startup</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Clicking repeatedly without lighting</div>
  </div>
  <p>The igniter is the ceramic component that glows red-hot to light the gas burner. A working igniter glows bright white and ignites gas within 45–60 seconds. A failing igniter glows dimly orange instead of bright white, takes longer than 90 seconds to light, or clicks repeatedly without the burner ever lighting. When it fails completely, no glow at all — the burner never fires. Igniter replacement: $280–350. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-igniter-replacement/">igniter replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<h2>How We Diagnose It On-Site</h2>
<p>We follow the same sequence on every no-heat call, working from cheapest to most expensive component. First: multimeter test on the thermal fuse — takes two minutes, open circuit means it's blown. This resolves about 60% of our calls right there. Second: check exhaust vent airflow — a clogged vent is usually what caused the fuse to blow, and we clear it before installing the new fuse. Third on electric dryers: test the heating element for continuity and correct resistance. Third on gas dryers: watch the igniter during a start attempt — does it glow bright white? If yes, test the gas valve coils. If dim orange or no glow, the igniter is the problem.</p>
<p>We don't recommend parts before we've tested. Replacing a heating element when the thermal fuse was the actual problem wastes your money and fixes nothing. The diagnostic fee is waived when you approve the repair — you only pay for what's actually broken.</p>

<h2>LG Error Codes Related to No Heat</h2>
<p><strong>d80, d90, d95</strong> — 80%, 90%, or 95% blockage in the exhaust vent. The dryer reduces or cuts off heat as a safety measure. If you see these codes, stop running the dryer — the vent needs to be cleared before the thermal fuse blows (if it hasn't already).</p>
<p><strong>tE1, tE2, tE3</strong> — Thermistor errors. The temperature sensor is reading incorrectly, causing erratic heating behavior. Less common but we see them on older DLGX models in Torrance and Long Beach.</p>
<p><strong>No code, just no heat</strong> — The most common presentation. Thermal fuse blows silently — no warning, no error code, the dryer just stops producing heat while everything else runs normally.</p>

<h2>Gas vs Electric — Why It Matters</h2>
<p>The repair is completely different depending on which type you have. If you're not sure: look at the back of the dryer. Gas models have a flexible gas line connected to the wall and a standard 120V plug. Electric models have a large 240V plug — 3 or 4 prongs, roughly fist-sized — and no gas connection. The thermal fuse applies to both. Everything else is different.</p>

<h2>Can You Still Use the Dryer?</h2>
<p>You can safely run air-dry or fluff cycles that don't use heat. Don't run heated cycles — on a failed heating element, repeated heat cycle attempts can stress the thermal fuse circuit. On a gas dryer with a failed igniter, the gas valve opens and tries to fire repeatedly without lighting, which isn't ideal for the valve over time. Better to wait for the repair.</p>

